body:
Here&#039;s why: lashes imply punishment for disobedience, typically for servants or religious followers. The word invokes a sense of retribution for misconduct to some discipline, which Illaoi sees herself as the &quot;educator and enlightener.&quot;

&gt; I am a teacher. Bilgewater will learn. 
&gt; They must be tested to grow.

Lashes are a former of penitence for one who would follow a religious code, ex. self-inflicted lashings were common way back when. So it would make sense that Illaoi&#039;s tentacles &quot;lash&quot; her foes to punish them for not following Nagakaboros&#039;s commands like she does. That same sort of emotion and depth doesn&#039;t exist with &quot;slam.&quot; It just sort of feels like, &quot;hey the tentacle slams down. Let&#039;s call it a slam attack.&quot;

Imo, calling them &quot;lashes&quot; evokes that sort of religious overtone that Illaoi radiates, and it&#039;s a very appropriate one to help demonstrate her character as opposed to &quot;slams.&quot;
